<p class="EnTeteTranscription">Johnston, John. An Account of Lake Superior, 1807-1809. An electronic transcription. MFTP #0037</p><div class="ContenuPage">
<p><span style="text-decoration:underline;">N</span><sup>o</sup><span style="text-decoration:underline;"> 7</span></p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">but agreeably relieving the eye by the soft contrast from Stern grandeur to rural simplicity.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">The beach is a fine white sand the land gently rising behind; in the left corner runs a beautiful limpid rill and as you approach you are led to think you see the ruins of ancient Temples, in which you are confirmed from perceiving an Arch standing quite apart from the neighbouring rocks, on the summit of which, (which is a Slab not 2 feet thick covered with 5 or 6 inches of mould) there are now growing several Birch and Pines.</p>
<p style="text-align:justify;">Not more than one quarter of a mile back from the Bay there is a lake perhaps a mile in circumference surrounded nearly by perpendicular rocks.  The little rill takes its rise from it.  It is very remarkable that on all the mountains that surround the Lake on either side, there are lakes, some of which are of considerable extent: &#8211; if to this be added the nature and inclination of the rocks, which is either Baysalt or freestone, the former of which bears evident masks of fusion,</p>

